observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

a.	Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Agriculturist, to trace the sale of the agricultural produce recorded as Merchandise Inventory and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balance of the said inventory account. 

Likewise, submit to the Audit Team the JEV pertaining to said adjustment including other documents relevant thereto;

b.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to maintain complete SLCs and SCs, respectively, for each item of supplies and materials or inventory account;

c. 	Require the Municipal Treasurer to consolidate the RIS issued weekly and prepare SSMI which shall serve as the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the issued supplies as expense; 


d. 	Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the LDRRMO, MHO, MAO and MSWDO, and establish effective internal control system by requiring the said departments to maintain complete and proper documentation including SCs, detailed distribution sheets for inventories held for distribution, logbook or other similar records to record transfer of stocks from the Municipal Treasurer to their respective storerooms and issuances therefrom;


e. 	Require the Inventory Committee to include in their periodic physical inventory of supplies the stocks under the custody of departments other than the Property Unit, and upon completion of the said count;


f. 	Direct the Municipal Accountant to review the physical count and require the said departments to submit copies of records maintained by them, have these reconciled and properly adjust the relevant inventory accounts so as to show the correct inventory balance; and


g. 	Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that JEVs pertaining to all adjustments made to inventory account are submitted to the Audit Team supported with RIS, SSMI, ICS, distribution sheets, logbooks and other similar records.

We reiterated the previous year’s recommendations that Management:

a.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the eight parcels of land identified in the name of the LGU at market value;



b. 	Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor to exhaust all possible means to document the legality of the unregistered parcels of land supported with TD only to facilitate the transfer of ownership in the name of the LGU;


c. 	Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor to reconcile their records pertaining to the parcels of land owned by the LGU; and

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate funds to cover all expenses to be incurred relative to land registration.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Observe proper accounting of semi-expendable properties using the prescribed new accounts;
Record the necessary reclassifying journal entries to correct the accounting errors for proper presentation of the expense and inventory accounts in the financial statements; and
Record the necessary adjustments for the reclassification of items recorded under the PPE account that fall below the ₱50,000.00 threshold retrospectively;
Require the Property Officer to:
Issue ICS for the issuance of semi-expendable properties totaling ₱792,111.47 and furnish copies thereof to the Audit Team;
Ensure to fill out properly the ICS by indicating all the necessary details, such as control numbers and inventory item numbers with consideration to the categorization of the items as to small-value or high-value; and
Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and assign separate ICS control numbers for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Property Officer to:
Maintain complete Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card (SPLC) and Semi-Expendable Property Card (SPC), respectively, for each item of semi-expendable properties; and
Formulate a policy/memorandum determining the estimated useful life of semi-expendable properties, and provide a copy thereof to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:

a. 	Require the BAC to ensure that:

•	The proper sequence of procurement procedures is followed, and the pertinent documents bear the actual date of preparation or issuance thereof;


•	In the absence of delegated authority in the conduct of alternative methods of procurement, the BAC will supervise and handle all the procurement procedures including the signing and releasing of the RFQs;


•	RFQs are fully and properly accomplished by indicating all the necessary information vital in the evaluation of the quotations including the document date and control number, deadline for the submission of the quotation, delivery period, ABC, PhilGEPS Registration Number, name of the authorized signatory, brand offered if applicable, price validity period and the date the supplier intends to deliver the goods;

•	A resolution or statement recommending to the HoPE the award of the contract to the Single or Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation is prepared or incorporated in the abstract of quotations in all procurements conducted through alternative methods;


•	In case of non-availability of stocks of ordinary office supplies and equipment from PS-DBM, request for a CNAS or other appropriate proofs as provided under GPPB Resolution No. 17-2020; and


•	The RFQ or Negotiation through Small Value Procurement for procurements that were actually conducted through other methods are not posted in the PhilGEPS website;

b. 	Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC Secretariat, to submit the Mayor’s Permit and PhilGEPS Registration Number, and 

Ensure that succeeding transactions are supported with complete documentation including the procurement plan.

To ensure that internal control procedures in handling repairs and maintenance of government vehicles and equipment are adequate and effective, we recommended that Management: 

a. 	Create an Inspection Committee with members capable of handling inspection of vehicles and equipment to be repaired;


b. 	Require the Municipal Treasurer to instruct all accountable officers or end-users of government vehicles and equipment to prepare Request for Pre-Repair Inspection indicating the property to be repaired with its property number, and the identified defects;


c. 	Require the Inspection Committee to prepare Pre-Repair Inspection Report based on the evaluation made;

d. 	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the Reports of Waste Materials for CY 2023 and ensure that succeeding transactions on repairs and maintenance are supported with the said report;

e. 	Upon completion of repairs or replacements made, instruct the Municipal Treasurer to request for Post-Repair Inspection from the Inspection Committee;


f. 	Require the Inspection Committee to prepare Post-Repair Inspection Report and forward the same to the Municipal Treasurer;

g. 	Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue a Certificate of Acceptance indicating clearly that the works or service done are in conformity with the specifications of the contract; and


h. 	Require the Municipal Treasurer to maintain a record of repairs for all the properties of the LGU which shall form part of the supporting documents of disbursements for repair and maintenance.

We recommended that Management:

a. 	Require the SAO/HRMO to initiate the formulation of internal rules and procedures on Overtime Services for review and approval of proper authorities;


b. 	Unless the circumstances of work or capacity of a particular department would not permit disruptions in personnel work schedule, require all unit heads to ensure that availing of CTO is prioritized instead of paying Overtime Pay which could be used by the LGU for other purposes;

c. 	Instruct all personnel to properly prepare their requests for authority to render overtime which will be the basis of the LCE or the Municipal Vice Mayor, as the case may be, in the preparation of Overtime Authority specifically indicating the personnel authorized to render overtime, the date and allowed duration, the committed work accomplishments, and the manner of compensation;

d. 	Instruct all department heads to ensure that Overtime Work Program is prepared to support the request to render overtime;

e. 	Require all personnel who were allowed to render overtime services to use the bundy clock of the LGU even beyond the regular workdays or hours, and prepare quantified accomplishment reports duly signed by them and the head of office or supervisors;

f. 	Require the concerned department heads to refund the amount claimed for overtime pay, net of withholding tax, totaling Ᵽ499,502.36; and


g. 	Require the SAO/HRMO to submit annually the Report on Overtime Services with Pay to CSC and DBM’s Budget and Management Bureau or Regional Office.

We reiterated the previous year’s recommendations that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the eight parcels of land identified in the name of the LGU at market value;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor to exhaust all possible means to document the legality of the unregistered parcels of land supported with TD only to facilitate the transfer of ownership in the name of the LGU;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor to reconcile their records pertaining to the parcels of land owned by the LGU; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate funds to cover all expenses to be incurred relative to land registration.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Treasurer to update and complete the PCs per category of PPE which are necessary to support the accuracy and reliability of the balances of PPE account in the financial statements;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare updated list of accountable officers and update the PAR every three years or every time there is a change of accountable officer/s;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records and trace, identify and classify any discrepancy in their reports; 
Require the GSO-Designate to identify and collate all unserviceable properties and conduct the necessary procedures on disposal of unserviceable properties;
Direct the Inventory Committee to avail the One-Time Cleansing program to establish the accuracy, accountability and existence of the PPE balances; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the RPCPPE per PPE classification and provide all necessary data required for proper identification of the PPE items.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct ocular inspection on the two constructed water systems and check the reasons why these were not operational from the time these were completed;
Require the Municipal Engineer to review the program of work of these projects and determine the coverage of the program in order to attain the main purpose;
Judiciously plan and evaluate future project proposals during the detailed engineering activities in the preliminary study to ensure that the project would be beneficial to the intended users; and
Seek out for a solution to make the above-mentioned projects functional for the attainment of the purpose of the program.

